can American Recordings of Porgy and Bess as Film and Cultural Criticism -- t‘‘Hollywood Has Taken on a New Color’’: The Yiddish Blackface of Samuel Goldwyn’s Porgy and Bess -- tCONTEMPORARY COMPILATIONS -- tPicturizing American Cinema: Hindi Film Songs and the Last Days of Genre -- tPopular Songs and Comic Allusion in Contemporary Cinema -- tGENDER AND TECHNOLOGY -- tThe Girl and the Phonograph; or the Vamp and the Machine Revisited -- tSelect Bibliography -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aFrom the silent era to the present day, popular music has been a key component of the film experience. Yet there has been little serious writing on film soundtracks that feature popular music. Soundtrack Available fills this gap, as its contributors provide detailed analyses of individual films as well as historical overviews of genres, styles of music, and approaches to film scoring.With a cross-cultural emphasis, the contributors focus on movies that use popular songs from a variety of genres, including country, bubble-gum pop, disco, classical, jazz, swing, French cabaret, and showtunes. The films discussed range from silents to musicals, from dramatic and avant-garde films to documentaries in India, France, England, Australia, and the United States. The essays examine both “nondiegetic” music in film—the score playing outside the story space, unheard by the characters, but no less a part of the scene from the perspective of the audience—and “diegetic” music—music incorporated into the shared reality of the story and the audience. They include analyses of music written and performed for films, as well as the now common practice of scoring a film with pre-existing songs. By exploring in detail how musical patterns and structures relate to filmic patterns of narration, character, editing, framing, and mise-en-scene, this volume demonstrates that pop music is a crucial element in the film experience. It also analyzes the life of the soundtrack apart from the film, tracing how popular music circulates and acquires new meanings when it becomes an official soundtrack.Contributors. Rick Altman, Priscilla Barlow, Barbara Ching, Kelley Conway, Corey Creekmur, Krin Gabbard, Jonathan Gill, Andrew Killick, Arthur Knight, Adam Knee, Jill Leeper, Neepa Majumdar, Allison McCracken, Murray Pomerance, Paul Ramaeker, Jeff Smith, Pamela Robertson Wojcik, Nabeel Zuberi  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aMotion picture musicxHistory and criticism. 0aMotion pictures and music. 0aPopular musicxHistory and criticism. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / Film & Video / History & Criticism.2bisacsh1 aAltman, Rick, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAltman, Rick.1 aBarlow, Priscilla, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBarlow, Priscilla.1 aChing, Barbara, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aConway, Kelley, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCreekmur, Corey K., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGabbard, Krin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGill, Jonathan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKillick, Andrew P., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKnee, Adam, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKnight, Arthur, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKnight, Arthur, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aLeeper, Jill, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMajumdar, Neepa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMccracken